    <div class="roadmap">
        <div class="step one">
          <h2>1. Decide on the Type of Adoption</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Domestic Adoption:</strong> Adopting a child from your own country.</li>
            <li><strong>International Adoption:</strong> Adopting a child from another country.</li>
            <li><strong>Foster Care Adoption:</strong> Adopting a child from the foster care system.</li>
            <li><strong>Private Adoption:</strong> Arranged through an agency or directly with birth parents.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="step two">
          <h2>2. Research and Choose an Adoption Agency</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Find a Licensed Adoption Agency:</strong> Ensure they are reputable and accredited.</li>
            <li><strong>Attend Orientation Sessions:</strong> Many agencies offer information sessions about the adoption process.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="step three">
          <h2>3. Complete an Application</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Submit Initial Application:</strong> Provide basic information about yourself and your interest in adoption.</li>
            <li><strong>Pay Application Fees:</strong> Some agencies require a fee to process the application.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="step four">
          <h2>4. Attend Training and Preparation Classes</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Pre-Adoption Education:</strong> Many agencies require prospective parents to attend training sessions on adoption-related issues.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="step five">
          <h2>5. Home Study Process</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Home Visits:</strong> A social worker will visit your home to assess your living environment.</li>
            <li><strong>Interviews:</strong> The social worker will conduct in-depth interviews with you and your family members.</li>
            <li><strong>Background Checks:</strong> Criminal, medical, and financial background checks will be performed.</li>
            <li><strong>References:</strong> Provide personal references who can vouch for your suitability as an adoptive parent.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="step six">
          <h2>6. Approval and Matching</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Home Study Report:</strong> Once approved, the agency will create a home study report summarizing the findings.</li>
            <li><strong>Matching Process:</strong> The agency will work to match you with a child who fits your preferences and capabilities.</li>
            <li><strong>Meeting the Child:</strong> In some cases, there will be an initial meeting to ensure compatibility.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="step seven">
          <h2>7. Legal Proceedings</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Placement:</strong> Once a match is made, the child is placed in your home for a trial period (varies by jurisdiction).</li>
            <li><strong>Post-Placement Visits:</strong> The social worker will conduct follow-up visits to ensure the child's well-being.</li>
            <li><strong>Finalization Hearing:</strong> After the trial period, a court hearing will be held to finalize the adoption. You will need to present the home study report and other required documents.</li>
            <li><strong>Adoption Decree:</strong> If the court is satisfied, an adoption decree will be issued, legally recognizing you as the child's parent.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="step eight">
          <h2>8. Post-Adoption Support</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Counseling and Support Groups:</strong> Many agencies offer post-adoption support to help families adjust.</li>
            <li><strong>Continued Education:</strong> Ongoing training and resources may be available to assist with any challenges.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="step nine">
          <h2>International Adoption Specifics</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Hague Convention Compliance:</strong> Ensure your adoption complies with the Hague Adoption Convention, which sets international standards.</li>
            <li><strong>Immigration Requirements:</strong> Complete necessary immigration procedures to bring the child to your home country.</li>
            <li><strong>Translation of Documents:</strong> Translate all required documents into the appropriate language.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="step ten">
          <h2>Additional Considerations</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Adoption Costs:</strong> Be prepared for various costs, including agency fees, legal fees, travel expenses (for international adoptions), and other miscellaneous expenses.</li>
            <li><strong>Emotional Readiness:</strong> Adoption can be a lengthy and emotional process. Ensure you have a strong support system in place.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
